[1] Multiple fungi, wheat, maize, soybean - Argentina
Date: 9 Oct 2009
Source: Diario Victoria, La Nacion report [in Spanish, trans.
Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
<http://www.diariovictoria.com.ar/2009/10/recomiendan-cuidar-la-sanidad-del-trigo/>

With the rainfall in some regions, foliar diseases have started to
appear [on wheat]. [Experts] stress the importance of surveillance
and the impact of the use of fungicides. Losses due to disease can
range from 10 to 20 percent on average.
Just as rainfall contributed to the growth of the cereal, it also
favoured the progress of foliar diseases. "Now there is concern and
dedication to care for and protect the wheat," said Marcelo Carmona,
Faculty of Agronomy, UBA [University of Buenos Aires].
In particular, the rains enabled the spread of yellow leaf spot in
much of the grain region. Rainfall is important for this disease.
Leaf rust was delayed due to the low temperatures. "However, already
there are foci of leaf rust from the north to the south of the Pampas
region," said the expert. "In areas such as Castelli, Maipu,
Pergamino, and southern Santa Fe, yellow leaf spot and the beginnings
of leaf rust are being reported," he added.
Cristina Palacio, another expert who performs constant monitoring in
southern Santa Fe, said: "Recent rains and warm temperatures favoured
the spread of wheat foliar diseases, especially yellow leaf spot and
septoria leaf spot." About leaf rust she said: "While intermediate
severity is not yet apparent, weekly monitoring is important because
of the favourable conditions [for the disease] in recent weeks."
[Byline: Fernando Bertello]
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
[An additional news story reports that Entre Rios is the area most
affected by wheat diseases. The presence of a rust, yellow and brown
leaf spots, some septoria and powdery mildew are mentioned. Rust on
maize crops in Santa Fe is also reported. In Cordoba, farmers are
alerted to watch soybean crops because of frogeye leafspot inoculum
found on seed
<http://www.eldiariodeparana.com.ar/textocomp.asp?id=180521> (in Spanish).
Additional reports of frogeye leafspot and rust in soybean (in
Spanish):
<http://www.eldiariodeparana.com.ar/textocomp.asp?id=180526> and
<http://www.colonbuenosaires.com.ar/semanariocolondoce/cgi-bin/hoy/archivo/2008/00001543.html>.
- Mod.DHA]
