[2] White mould, peanuts - Nicaragua
Date: 19 Oct 2009
Source: La Prensa [in Spanish, trans. Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
<http://www.laprensa.com.ni/archivo/2009/octubre/19/noticias/regionales/355425.shtml>

Low rainfall is affecting around 25 000 ha [60 000 acres)] of peanuts
in Chinandega, which are exposed to an increase in white mould, a
harmful fungus that stains the grain, reduces the yield by 10
percent, and increases the cost of production.
Producers fear that, for now, not even fungicide application would
remove the pressure on the plants because of the drought. Agronomists
explained to reporters from La Prensa that it is not effective to
counter the disease without rain.
A month before the harvest, the weather is overwhelming the
producers. One of them said that the plantations in Chinandega
apparently are lush, but the fungus is imperceptible, the reason he
fears that in one month the pest could affect thousands of acres in
the whole country. "The problem is that there is a period with good
weather and no rains, but when they come suddenly, diseases appear in
peanuts," he explained.
In West Nicaragua, after the disappearance of cotton cultivation,
peanuts became an exportable alternative, with more than 100
producers in the area.
[Byline: Saul Martinez]
--
