[3] Phomopsis, soybean and ear rots, maize - USA
Date: 18 Oct 2009
Source: Palladium-Item [edited]
<http://www.pal-item.com/article/20091018/NEWS01/910180313/1008/Wet-weather-delays-harvest-in-Indiana--Ohio>

Wet weather is delaying harvest across Indiana and Ohio, and fungal
diseases in corn and soybeans have damaged what was expected to be a
bumper crop. Ear rot in corn and phomopsis seed decay in soybeans are
reducing grain quality this year [2009], diseases that thrive in wet
conditions, plant pathologists say.
Phomopsis is typically rare, but conditions this summer [2009] with
frequent rains and now delayed harvest are the perfect environments
for the soybean pathogen to take hold, said Anne Dorrance, Ohio State
University.
Diplodia and gibberella ear rots are being seen in many Indiana
cornfields. Diplodia ear rot is throughout the state, especially in
the northeast and southeast, said Charles Woloshuk, Purdue. Infection
ranges from only a small percentage up to 30 percent of the ears, he
said. "If it's gibberella ear rot, then there's concern about the
mycotoxin deoxynivalenol or DON, as well as zearalenone. If suspect,
the grain should be tested, especially if it's to be fed to
livestock," Woloshuk said.
[In Ohio, gibberella is reported to be the most prevalent ear rot
this year [2009], however, reports of diplodia in some fields have
also been received:
<http://www.zanesvilletimesrecorder.com/article/20091019/NEWS01/910190320>.
Particularly severe diplodia levels are also reported from the entire
corn belt region, and damage exceeding 50 percent due to mouldy maize
has been reported from some parts:
<http://www.agweb.com/get_article.aspx?pageid=153960>. - Mod.DHA]
